 "conclusion": "The mean-pool floor barely moves. Learned nonneg per-encoder weights lower misID from 3.81% to 3.45% (-0.35pp, ~9% relative), consistent across all 3 disjoint splits -- but this ENTIRE gain is reproduced by the trivial rule 'downweight the redundant ecapa member' (drop_ecapa=3.50%), i.e. member pruning, not richer fusion. The 'stronger fusion' the reviewer names -- stacking logistic regression over per-encoder cosines -- does NOT beat mean-pool; it is WORSE (4.21% linear, 4.60% quadratic), because a pairwise same/diff logistic objective is misaligned with rank-1 identification. Net: learned fusion does not meaningfully lower the closed-set misID floor."
